Yes, React has a built-in function called `useCallback` that allows you to memoize a function so that it's not recreated on every render. Here's an example of how you can use it:

```jsx
import { useCallback } from 'react';

function MyComponent() {
  const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
    console.log('Button clicked!');
  }, []);

  return (
    <button onClick={handleClick}>
      Click me!
    </button>
  );
}
```

In this example, `handleClick` is a memoized function that will only be recreated if the dependencies in the second argument (`[]` in this case) change.

If you want to memoize a function with dependencies, you can pass an array of dependencies to `useCallback`. For example:

```jsx
import { useCallback } from 'react';

function MyComponent({ name }) {
  const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
    console.log(`Button clicked by ${name}!`);
  }, [name]);

  return (
    <button onClick={handleClick}>
      Click me!
    </button>
  );
}
```

In this example, `handleClick` will be recreated if `name` changes.

